{"TopicId":133142,"ForumId":16,"TopicTitle":"What exactly is the length of a Kerbin day?","CreatedByName":"CaelumEtAstra","CreatedById":109360,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-02-28T22:25:02Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"CaelumEtAstra","CreatedById":109360,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-02-28T22:25:02Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u0027m setting up a RemoteTech network in a keostationary orbit. Before 1.0, the day was 59h, 59m, 59s. Now I\u0027m hearing that it is exactly 6h. I\u0027m asking so I can get the orbital period right to prevent the satellites from drifting. Thanks in advance!\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Chaos_Klaus","CreatedById":140720,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-02-28T22:52:20Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe wiki is your friend:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022http://wiki.kerbalspaceprogram.com/wiki/Kerbin\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttp://wiki.kerbalspaceprogram.com/wiki/Kerbin\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nLook for sidereal rotation period. It\u0027s not exactly\u00A06h.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"FancyMouse","CreatedById":142946,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-02-28T23:48:41Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt was a recent change (post 1.0) that makes a solar day a whole day, so sidereal rotation period is a few seconds shorter.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFound the thread:\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ciframe data-embedcontent=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/topic/117077-new-measurement-of-kerbins-sidereal-day-not-6-hours/\u0026amp;do=embed\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"GoSlash27","CreatedById":111526,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-03-01T01:36:03Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWell... that depends on what you call a \u0022day\u0022. \u003Cimg alt=\u0022;)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022true\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_wink.gif\u0022 title=\u0022;)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nA \u0022solar\u0022 day (sunrise/ sunset/ clocks) is precisely 6 hours.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0A \u0022sidereal\u0022 day (Kerbin\u0027s rotational period in inertial space; WRT distant stars) is 5 hours, 59 minutes, 9.4 seconds\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBest,\u003Cbr\u003E\n-Slashy\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222016-03-01T01:42:38Z\u0022 title=\u002203/01/2016 01:42  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00228 yr\u0022\u003EMarch 1, 2016\u003C/time\u003E by GoSlash27\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Kerbart","CreatedById":78303,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-03-01T01:39:14Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222436073\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022133142\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221456796163\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022111526\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022GoSlash27\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n3 minutes ago, GoSlash27 said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWell... that depends on what you call a \u0022day\u0022. \u003Cimg alt=\u0022;)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022true\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_wink.gif\u0022 title=\u0022;)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBest,\u003Cbr\u003E\n-Slashy\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nLet\u0027s call it \u0022a day!\u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"OhioBob","CreatedById":128005,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-03-01T04:46:26Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222434325\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022133142\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221456703321\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022142946\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022FancyMouse\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nOn \u200E2\u200E/\u200E28\u200E/\u200E2016 at 6:48 PM, FancyMouse said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt was a recent change (post 1.0) that makes a solar day a whole day, so sidereal rotation period is a few seconds shorter.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFound the thread:\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ciframe data-embedcontent=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/topic/117077-new-measurement-of-kerbins-sidereal-day-not-6-hours/\u0026amp;do=embed\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe thread to which you link is from before the\u00A0change to the 6 hour solar day.\u00A0 The measurements presented in that thread are\u00A0no longer applicable.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFor a keostationary orbit, it is the sidereal rotation period that you want to match.\u00A0\u00A0Starting with version 1.05, Kerbin\u0027s sidereal\u00A0rotation period is 21549.4251830898 seconds.\u00A0 This period is attained with an orbit having a semi-major axis of 3463334.0595 meters.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222016-03-01T18:59:16Z\u0022 title=\u002203/01/2016 06:59  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00228 yr\u0022\u003EMarch 1, 2016\u003C/time\u003E by OhioBob\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"}]}